\section{Introduction}

Long-running LLM agents combine agent-local memory with shared external knowledge. Prior work has made inside-trial and cross-trial memories increasingly adaptive~\cite{zhang2024survey,hu2025memory,du2026memory,packer2023memgpt,zhong2023memorybank,weng2025amem}, but the shared RAG-backed knowledge store is still often managed as static infrastructure. We focus on this shared external memory: a long-lived corpus-backed KB whose hot tier must stay aligned with changing multi-user demand.

The first question is whether this phenomenon is real enough to matter in deployed RAG systems. User-generated queries naturally change over time based on events in the world and the evolution of language~\cite{yang2025murr}; in multi-user LLM reasoning systems, this appears as a shift in the topic distribution of incoming queries, not merely as a change in the facts available to the system. We term this phenomenon \emph{query distribution drift}. Figure~\ref{fig:motivation0} provides direct empirical evidence in the LLM setting: monthly topic mixtures in WildChat-1M real ChatGPT conversation logs shift measurably from month to month (panel~a), and Google Trends interest for five LLM application domains reweights substantially over a multi-year horizon (panel~b). Together with prior findings on long-tail and temporally shifting RAG demand~\cite{vu2023freshllms,zhou2025livesearchbench,peng2025uaeval4rag}, these signals establish that persistent shared-KB maintenance is a demand-alignment problem rather than only a freshness problem.

The next question is what this looks like on a realistic retrieval workload. We therefore begin with StreamingQA~\cite{liska2022streamingqa}, a 14-year real-news QA benchmark whose five historical eras induce piecewise demand drift over a static cold corpus. Figure~\ref{fig:streamingqa} shows the core empirical pattern: once demand crosses into a new era, frozen and recency-/frequency-based hot-tier policies quickly collapse, because they keep the wrong documents hot. QueryDriven already helps by reacting to repeated support failures in the query stream, but OnDemand only recovers the highest recall by paying a much larger cold-tier latency cost, which we make explicit in Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}c.

Why do the standard baselines fail here? Existing dynamic RAG work does not use the query stream itself as the update trigger: temporal RAG refreshes facts when the world state changes~\cite{hoh2025,dynaquest2025}; index-level methods ingest new documents~\cite{guo2024lightrag,guti2025hipporag2}; editing and pruning methods reshape an existing corpus~\cite{chen2024recipe,zero-rag2025}; caching methods favor recent or frequent access~\cite{comrag2025,jin2024ragcache,wu2025streamingrag}; and log-driven refresh waits for delayed answerability or evaluation feedback~\cite{peng2025uaeval4rag,es2023ragas}. In our static-corpus cache setting, these recency/frequency baselines do not receive document creation timestamps; their time signal comes only from cache access or supply-side samples. A timestamp-aware TTL/LRU policy is appropriate for document-stream ingestion, but would be a temporal oracle for a pre-existing corpus. Without that oracle, these methods systematically mistime updates under demand drift.

If supply-side and temporal heuristics miss the shift, the next question is whether the query stream alone is already enough. To isolate that point, we study a deliberately minimal admission rule, \emph{QueryDriven} (QD), which accumulates demand over candidate support documents retrieved from the cold corpus and rewrites the hot cache only when repeated query failures justify the write. Even this simple no-timestamp rule substantially outperforms LRU, GPTCache-style, and MemGPT-style caches in direct-evidence settings (Figures~\ref{fig:streamingqa} and~\ref{fig:motivation1}a), where the query usually names or strongly implies the needed evidence. However, in complex multi-hop settings (Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}b), QD brings only small gains: document replacement driven by query embeddings is the wrong abstraction when answering requires connecting entities across a reasoning path, because the query may mention only the first-hop entity while the reusable evidence lies in second-hop documents. Crucially, enriching the admission policy with document arrival timestamps---as in log-driven or frequency-decay caches---does not close this gap: the missing signal is not \emph{when} a document arrived but \emph{which} second-hop document completes the reasoning chain, a relationship that neither query embeddings nor temporal metadata expose. This single-hop/multi-hop gap motivates a drift-aware cache management framework that, instead of always replacing documents from the query embedding, detects when query-only replacement is failing and falls back to either online cold-tier retrieval or entity-level evidence expansion; the concrete mechanism is developed in Section~\ref{sec:method}.

Beyond the real StreamingQA study, we also include controlled abrupt- and gradual-shift benchmarks to diagnose where a minimal query-driven rule works and where it breaks. We defer the construction details of these controlled datasets to the experimental setup; in the introduction, we use them only to expose the empirical pattern in Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}.

