    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.98\textwidth]{motivation/paper_figs/intro/fig0_intro_user_query_topic_drift.pdf}
    \caption{\textbf{Multi-user demand drifts even when the underlying corpus does not.} \textit{(a)} Monthly topic proportions in 32.5K WildChat-1M English ChatGPT conversations~\cite{zhao2024wildchat} (2023.04--2024.04): the dominant topic shifts substantially across months without any change to world facts or to the underlying knowledge corpus. \textit{(b)} Google Trends weekly search interest for five LLM application domains (2022--2026): user attention reweights from chatbot-centric toward coding, education, and agent use cases. These signals motivate \emph{query distribution drift}---demand alignment, not freshness---as the first-class challenge for the hot tier of a multi-user agent's shared external memory.}
    \label{fig:motivation0}
\end{figure*}

\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.98\textwidth]{motivation/paper_figs/intro/fig1_intro_streamingqa_static_cache.pdf}
    \caption{\textbf{Hot-tier admission policies on a real 14-year news stream (StreamingQA~\cite{liska2022streamingqa}, ICML 2022).} Cold corpus = 29{,}819 documents (\emph{static}, all pre-existing on day 1, no creation timestamps exposed); hot KB = 750 slots ($\sim$40$\times$ admission ratio). Five historical eras (R1--R5, 2008--2020) drive piecewise topic shift over the 50 windows. Frozen and recency-/frequency-based caches (Static, LRU, GPTCache-, MemGPT-style) all collapse to near-zero Recall@5 once demand crosses into a new era; even the simple QueryDriven rule is markedly better without using document timestamps, while on-demand fetch remains the high-quality but higher-latency upper adaptive route (Fig.~\ref{fig:motivation1}c).}
    \label{fig:streamingqa}
\end{figure*}

\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.98\textwidth]{motivation/paper_figs/intro/fig2_intro_qd_diagnostic.pdf}
    \caption{\textbf{The single-hop/multi-hop gap that motivates our framework.} \textit{(a)} Single-hop direct-evidence (HotpotQA-comp, pool=200K, KB=21K): query-side failures are strong admission signals, so the minimal QueryDriven rule already outperforms supply-side and recency/frequency cache baselines without document timestamps. \textit{(b)} Multi-hop (2WikiMultihopQA, pool=67K, KB=6.7K): a query-only replacement rule is insufficient once useful evidence must be reached through bridge entities. \textit{(c)} Hot-tier cost/quality trade-off: QueryDriven serves from the hot tier (1.6\,ms/query) while OnDemand obtains higher recall by querying the cold tier online (7.1\,ms/query); these two operating points bracket the design space that the proposed framework must navigate.}
    \label{fig:motivation1}
\end{figure*}

\textbf{In summary, our main contributions are as follows:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=2pt,topsep=2pt]
    \item We formalize \emph{query distribution drift} as a distinct challenge for the hot-tier admission problem in two-tier RAG systems, including the shared knowledge modules of RAG-augmented agent deployments.
    \item We characterize when a minimal query-driven admission rule is
    sufficient and when it is not: query-side failures are strong admission
    signals in direct-evidence settings, but query-only replacement breaks down
    in multi-hop settings where useful evidence is reached through bridge entities.
    \item We show that static, supply-side, and recency/frequency cache strategies
    fail to infer demand drift when document timestamps are unavailable, causing
    mistimed or wasted hot-tier updates.
    \item We develop a drift-aware cache management framework that detects when
    the hot tier is misaligned with incoming demand and routes the response
    between hot-tier replacement, online cold-tier retrieval, and entity-level
    evidence expansion (Section~\ref{sec:method}).
\end{itemize}


\section{Proposed Framework}\label{sec:method}

We instantiate the drift-aware cache management framework as three coupled components: a drift detector that decides \emph{when} the hot tier is misaligned with incoming demand, a failure classifier that decides \emph{how} the misalignment should be repaired, and three repair routines that map to the empirical regimes identified in Figures~\ref{fig:streamingqa} and~\ref{fig:motivation1}.

\paragraph{Drift detector.}
Let $H_t \subset \mathcal{C}$ denote the set of documents in the hot tier at the start of window $t$, where $\mathcal{C}$ is the static cold corpus. We summarise both the incoming queries and the hot tier in the same dense embedding space used for retrieval. Let $\bar{\mathbf{q}}_t$ be the mean of the query embeddings in window $t$ and $\bar{\mathbf{h}}_t$ the mean of the document embeddings in $H_t$. We track the misalignment $d_t = 1 - \cos(\bar{\mathbf{q}}_t, \bar{\mathbf{h}}_t)$ together with the fraction $u_t$ of queries in window $t$ whose top-$K$ retrieval from $H_t$ contains no document above a similarity threshold $\tau$ (an unsupported-query rate). Drift is declared in window $t$ when either $d_t > \mu_d + k \sigma_d$ or $u_t > \mu_u + k \sigma_u$, where $(\mu, \sigma)$ are the running mean and standard deviation maintained over a sliding history of $W$ past windows and $k \in \{2,3\}$ is a sensitivity hyper-parameter. This detector requires no document timestamps and adds only $O(1)$ statistics per window beyond the retrieval already performed for serving.

\paragraph{Failure classifier.}
Each unsupported query $q$ that triggers the drift detector is routed by inspecting its first-hop retrieval against $H_t$. Let $s_1, s_2, \dots$ be the top-$K$ similarity scores. We distinguish three failure regimes:
(i) \textbf{R1 — direct-evidence miss in the cold corpus}: $s_1$ is high but the supporting documents identified by query expansion lie in $\mathcal{C} \setminus H_t$, i.e., the hot tier is missing a document that already exists in the cold corpus;
(ii) \textbf{R2 — cold-only evidence}: every $s_i < \tau$, indicating that the relevant evidence is unlikely to be present in the hot tier and must be served by the cold tier on this query;
(iii) \textbf{R3 — multi-hop bridge}: $s_1$ is high and $H_t$ does contain the first-hop evidence, but the query requires a second document that is not retrievable from the query embedding alone.

\paragraph{Repair routines.}
We assign one repair routine to each regime:
(R1) \emph{Demand-aware replacement} extends the QueryDriven baseline introduced in the introduction: failed queries accumulate evidence over support documents retrieved from $\mathcal{C}$, and once the cumulative demand for a candidate document $d \in \mathcal{C} \setminus H_t$ exceeds an admission threshold, $d$ is admitted into $H_t$ in place of the hot-tier document with the lowest recent demand. The hot-tier serving latency is preserved because admission updates are amortised over many queries.
(R2) \emph{Online cold-tier retrieval} bypasses $H_t$ for the current query and serves directly from $\mathcal{C}$, as in OnDemand. The cost/quality trade-off in Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}c shows this is the right operating point when no nearby hot-tier evidence exists; persisting the fetched documents into $H_t$ is then governed by the same demand counter as R1.
(R3) \emph{Entity-level evidence expansion} addresses the multi-hop case in Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}b. We pre-compute a one-time inverted index from cold-corpus entities to documents using lightweight named-entity extraction over $\mathcal{C}$. At query time, after retrieving the first-hop document $d_1$ from $H_t$, we extract its entities and use the inverted index to fetch a small candidate set of second-hop documents from $\mathcal{C}$. These candidates are then re-ranked against the original query and the highest-scoring ones are admitted into $H_t$ under the same R1 demand counter. This recovers the bridge evidence that a query-only embedding cannot reach, while the entity index itself is built once offline.

\paragraph{System cost accounting.}
Beyond Recall@5, we report (a) the per-window detector cost (mean-vector and threshold update), (b) the per-admission update cost (one ANN insert and one re-encode), and (c) the per-query serving latency, separated into hot-tier serving time and the additional cold-tier round-trip when the failure classifier routes to R2 or R3. These are the same axes shown in Figure~\ref{fig:motivation1}c, so the framework can be placed on the same cost/quality plane as QueryDriven and OnDemand and reported as a single trade-off curve.
